{"type":"message","id":"35c1140b","parentId":"30a9ea4b","timestamp":"2026-03-23T13:35:47.835Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me look at the fix. The crash is at line 142, which is:\n`$rawContent = $choices[0].message.content`\n\nThe issue is that even though we check `$null -ne $choices` and `$choices.Count -gt 0`, `$choices[0]` can still be null in some edge cases (like if the API returns an array with a null element, or if `$choices` is not actually an array but some other object).\n\nThe fix is to use safe navigation operators or restructure. Let me use:\n\n```powershell\n$rawContent = $choices[0].message.content\n```\n\nChange to:\n\n\nRefining the null check approach...\n\nActually, looking at the original code again, the crash must be happening at `$choices[0]` itself since the error says \"Cannot index into a null array\" — that's PowerShell's way of reporting that `$choices` is null when we try to index it, not that the first element is null. The null check should be catching this, so something's off with how the condition is being evaluated.\n\nI need to refactor this to be more defensive — checking if `$choices` is actually an array with elements before trying to access them.","thinkingSignature":"65547b19bc7fdf5f06556fcbf836edee3b504a39015daf8755f277d4dd3d1532"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_u9mdqy5is2n8_1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\sandbox\\pulse.ps1","old_string":"        $choices = $resp.choices\n        if ($null -ne $choices -and $choices.Count -gt 0) {\n            $rawContent = $choices[0].message.content\n            if ($null -eq $rawContent) {\n                Write-Host \"[DEBUG] content is NULL. Full choice: $($choices[0] | ConvertTo-Json -Depth 3)\"\n                $llmResponse = \"\"\n            } else {\n                Write-Host \"[DEBUG] content length: $($rawContent.Length)\"\n                $llmResponse = $rawContent\n            }\n    