{"type":"message","id":"2e855bbf","parentId":"b0a92cb3","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:03:06.764Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, the `modal deploy` approach might not work cleanly without actually testing the deploy. Also, the approach above has a problem — `run_commands` in Modal images run at build time, not runtime. Let me rethink.\n\nA cleaner approach for Modal: \n1. Use a Container with the `modal.Image` containing Ollama installed\n2. Run `ollama serve` as the container's main process via `@modal.entrypoint()`\n3. Expose port 11434 via `modal.web_endpoint()`\n\nActually, Modal's approach for running a long-running server is different. Let me use `@modal.asgi_app()` or create a web endpoint that proxies to a subprocess running ollama.\n\n\nI need to clarify how Modal actually handles persistent processes versus web endpoints — whether `ollama serve` should be launched in the background within a web handler, or if there's a better pattern for long-running services on Modal.\n\nThe core issue is that web endpoints are stateless and get recreated for each request, so I can't rely on a persistent background process. Instead, I should use Modal's `Proxy` object to create a networked service that runs ollama as a long-running container with a TCP port exposed, which is Modal's recommended approach for running servers. I need to figure out the right Modal primitives for this—a cls with @modal.method and a @modal.web_endpoint, then start ollama serve as a background process that gets cleaned up on exit.\n\nActually, looking at Modal's documentation more carefully, the pattern for running something like Ollama is to use @modal.container after building an image with the installer, then start the server as a background process within that persistent container context.\n\nThe tricky part is that the background process needs to stay alive, so I need to handle it carefully within the modal.runner context. Let me try a simpler approach first—just running ollama directly in a container with a web endpoint that proxies requests to it.\n\nI'll write a straightforward deployment file using Modal's latest API, though I'm not entirely confident on all the syntax without checking the docs more carefully.","thinkingSignature":"45374013252dd78d42f4e467121054c375d94fffa9fc1e42cf48b4f43ccf4103"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_j7ljl7cxwtnj_1","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"modal run --help 2>&1 | Select-Object -First 20"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":72802,"output":461,"cacheRead":13593,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":86856,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774274567177}}
{"type":"message","id":"47b51f72","parentId":"2e855bbf","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:03:08.607Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_j7ljl7cxwtnj_1","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Usage: modal run [OPTIONS] FUNC_REF\r\n\r\n  Run a Modal function or local entrypoint.\r\n\r\n  `FUNC_REF` should be of the format `{file or module}::{function name}`.\r\n  Alternatively, you can refer to the function via the app:\r\n\r\n  `{file or module}::{app variable name}.{function name}`\r\n\r\n  **Examples:**\r\n\r\n  To run the hello_world function (or local entrypoint) in my_app.py:\r\n\r\n  ``` modal run my_app.py::hello_world ```\r\n\r\n  If your module only has a single app and your app has a single local\r\n  entrypoint (or single function), you can omit the app and function parts:\r\n\r\n  ``` modal run my_app.py ```"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":1799,"aggregated":"Usage: modal run [OPTIONS] FUNC_REF\r\n\r\n  Run a Modal function or local entrypoint.\r\n\r\n  `FUNC_REF` should be of the format `{file or module}::{function name}`.\r\n  Alternatively, you can refer to the function via the app:\r\n\r\n  `{file or module}::{app variable name}.{function name}`\r\n\r\n  **Examples:**\r\n\r\n  To run the hello_world function (or local entrypoint) in my_app.py:\r\n\r\n  ``` modal run my_app.py::hello_world ```\r\n\r\n  If your module only has a single app and your app has a single local\r\n  entrypoint (or single function), you can omit the app and function parts:\r\n\r\n  ``` modal run my_app.py ```","cwd":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\.openclaw\\workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774274588583}}
{"type":"message","id":"936714cd","parentId":"47b51f72","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:03:38.890Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK, so `modal run` is for running a specific function. But what I need is a long-running service that hosts Ollama. Let me write the proper Modal app.\n\nActually, the right approach for Modal is:\n1. Define an image with Ollama pre-installed\n2. Use `@modal.wsgi_app()` or create a web service\n\nLet me write a cleaner version. The trick is:\n- For `modal deploy`, the app runs as a long-running service\n- For Ollama, we need to keep the server process running\n\nThe best pattern in Modal for this is:\n\n```python\nfrom modal import method, web_endpoint\n\n@app.cls(gpu=\"A100\", ...)\n\n\n```\n\nBuilding the container image...\n\n```\n\nWait, I'm realizing the background process approach won't work in Modal since the function needs to return to handle the web request. Let me think about this differently — maybe I should just use Modal's infrastructure directly without trying to run ollama as a background service, or look into whether Modal has a specific pattern for proxying to external services like they mention in their docs. I'll write out a working example that starts ollama serve as a subprocess, waits for it to be ready, then handles web requests by proxying to it.\n\nActually, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me check if Modal has example apps for running external services like Ollama directly, or if I should just run it as a subprocess within the web handler itself. A subprocess approach might work if the cold start overhead isn't prohibitive, but for frequent requests that could be expensive.\n\nActually, I should look into Modal's GPU container support more carefully. They have a pattern where you can run persistent containers with GPU access, which would let me keep Ollama running in the background instead of restarting it for each request.\n\n```","thinkingSignature":"bb96f7cada783206a6a15964b021aca1172c5c7af50489e0f20138cd10a73d06"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_0zb92eplt8l9_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\Claw\\projects\\spark\\deploy\\modal_ollama.py","content":"\"\"\"\nSPARK Ollama GPU endpoint on Modal\nDeploy: modal deploy spark.deploy.modal_ollama\nEndpoint: https://spark-ollama-qwen.modal.run\n\"\"\"\n\nimport modal\n\napp = modal.App(\"spark-ollama\")\n\n# Build an image with Ollama installed\nollama_image = (\n    modal.Image.debian_slim(python_version=\"3.11\")\n    .pip_install(\"requests\", \"httpx\")\n    .run_commands(\n        \"curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh\",\n        \"ollama pull qwen2.5:7b\",\n    )\n    .env({\"OLLAMA_MODELS\": \"/root/.ollama\"})\n)\n\n\n@app.cls(\n    image=ollama_image,\n    gpu=\"A100\",\n    memory=32768,\n    container_idle_timeout=600,\n    timeout=3600,\n)\nclass OllamaEndpoint:\n    \"\"\"\n    Long-running Ollama container. \n    Cold starts ~3-5 min (pulling model). Then runs until idle timeout.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    @modal.build(image=ollama_image)\n    @modal.run(image=ollama_image)\n    @modal.enter()\n    def start_server(self):\n        \"\"\"Start ollama serve as background process, wait for it to be ready.\"\"\"\n        import subprocess, time, os, signal, requests\n\n        self._process = subprocess.Popen(\n            [\"ollama\", \"serve\"],\n            stdout=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            preexec_fn=os.setsid,\n        )\n\n        # Poll until Ollama is ready\n        for _ in range(30):\n            try:\n                r = requests.get(\"http://localhost:11434\", timeout=2)\n                if r.status_code == 200:\n                    break\n            except Exception:\n                pass\n            time.sleep(2)\n        else:\n            raise RuntimeError(\"Ollama failed to start within 60s\")\n\n        print(\"[spark-ollama] Ollama ready on localhost:11434\")\n\n    @modal.exit()\n    def stop_server(self):\n        \"\"\"Clean up the ollama server process.\"\"\"\n        import os, signal\n        try:\n            os.killpg(os.getpgid(self._process.pid), signal.SIGTERM)\n        except Exception:\n            pass\n\n    @web_endpoint(label=\"spark-ollama-qwen\", method=\"POST\")\n    def generate(self, body: dict):\n        \"\"\"\n        Proxy generate request to local Ollama.\n        body: { prompt: str, model?: str, options?: { temperature?, num_predict? } }\n        \"\"\"\n        import requests, json\n\n        payload = {\n            \"model\": body.get(\"model\", \"qwen2.5:7b\"),\n            \"prompt\": body.get(\"prompt\", \"\"),\n            \"stream\": False,\n            \"options\": body.get(\"options\", {}),\n        }\n        resp = requests.post(\n            \"http://localhost:11434/api/generate\",\n            json=payload,\n            timeout=body.get(\"options\", {}).get(\"num_predict\", 600) // 10 + 60,\n        )\n        resp.raise_for_status()\n        return {\"response\": resp.json().get(\"response\", \"\"), \"model\": payload[\"model\"]}\n\n    @web_endpoint(label=\"spark-ollama-qwen\", method=\"GET\")\n    def health(self):\n        return {\n            \"status\": \"ok\",\n            \"service\": \"spark-ollama\",\n            \"model\": \"qwen2.5:7b\",\n            \"note\": \"POST /generate with {prompt, model?, options?} to generate\",\n        }\n\n\n@app.local_entrypoint()\ndef test():\n    \"\"\"Quick local test — just verify the module loads.\"\"\"\n    print(\"spark-ollama module loaded OK\")\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":73430,"output":1208,"cacheRead":13593,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":88231,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774274588613}}
{"type":"message","id":"ae983d57","parentId":"936714cd","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:03:38.958Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_function_0zb92eplt8l9_1","toolName":"write","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully wrote 3146 bytes to C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\Claw\\projects\\spark\\deploy\\modal_ollama.py"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774274618936}}
{"type":"message","id":"ac746bad","parentId":"ae983d57","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:04:13.283Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Actually, looking at this more carefully, the `@modal.build`, `@modal.run`, and `@modal.enter()` decorators on the same function won't work as intended. The `start_server` function decorated with `@modal.enter()` will run on every container start (including after idle timeout). The `@modal.build()` decorator is for building the image.\n\nA cleaner Modal approach: let me just try to deploy it and see what happens. But first, let me make sure the syntax is correct.\n\nActually, looking at Modal's docs more carefully, the decorator ordering should be:\n```python\n@modal.build()  # runs during image build\n\n\n@modal.enter()  # runs when container starts\n```\n\nThese are separate lifecycle hooks on different methods. For the class itself:\n- `@modal.cls(gpu=\"A100\", ...)` defines the class\n- `@modal.build()` on a method = runs during `modal deploy` when building the image\n- `@modal.enter()` on a method = runs when the container starts\n- `@modal.exit()` on a method = runs when the container stops\n\nThe correct pattern for a class with gpu and persistent background process:\n```python\n@modal.cls(gpu=\"A100\", ...)\nclass OllamaEndpoint:\n    @modal.build()  # runs during image build\n    def build(self):\n        # This is wrong — build doesn't run shell commands\n```\n\nI'm mixing up when these decorators actually execute. The `build` decorator doesn't run shell commands during deployment, it just marks a method to run during the build phase. I need to use `run_commands` on the image itself instead, and keep the lifecycle methods separate for when the container actually starts and stops. Let me restructure this with the proper decorator order and cleaner separation between build-time setup and runtime lifecycle. I'm realizing the `run_commands` in `Image.debian_slim()` executes during the `modal deploy` build phase, which means `ollama pull qwen2.5:7b` would run on Modal's build servers rather than in the final image—so the model wouldn't actually be persisted in the container itself.\n\nLooking at Modal's documentation, I think the right approach is to use a `Stub` with a `Image` that installs Ollama during build, then in the `@enter()` lifecycle method, start the Ollama server as a background subprocess and handle cleanup in `@exit()`. I need to restructure this to keep `@build()` and `@enter()` as separate methods—`@build()` handles the image creation (running the install commands and pulling the model), while `@enter()` is where the runtime setup happens, like starting the server process.","thinkingSignature":"b42341d0c20bfc05526de8552c9bf8b1f48672c9ed75bb8b9283d237e73b3f2f"},{"type":"text","text":"Let me rewrite with the correct Modal decorator pattern — `@build()` and `@enter()` need to be separate methods.\n"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_function_djl70bboezf8_1","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:\\Users\\Zwmar\\Claw\\projects\\spark\\deploy\\modal_ollama.py","content":"\"\"\"\nSPARK Ollama GPU endpoint on Modal\nDeploy: modal deploy spark.deploy.modal_ollama\nEndpoint: https://spark-ollama-qwen-{workspace}.modal.run\n\"\"\"\n\nimport modal\n\napp = modal.App(\"spark-ollama\")\n\n# Build an image with Ollama + model baked in\nollama_image = (\n    modal.Image.debian_slim(python_version=\"3.11\")\n    .pip_install(\"requests\", \"httpx\")\n    .run_commands(\n        \"curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh\",\n    )\n    .run_function(\n        lambda: modal.Function.lookup(\"spark-ollama\", \"pull_model\")\n        if False\n        else None,\n    )\n)\n\n\n@app.cls(\n    image=ollama_image,\n    gpu=\"A100\",\n    memory=32768,\n    container_idle_timeout=600,\n    timeout=3600,\n)\nclass OllamaEndpoint:\n    \"\"\"\n    Long-running Ollama container on A100.\n    Cold starts ~2-3 min (ollama serve init). Model already pulled at build time.\n    \"\"\"\n\n    @modal.build()\n    def build(self):\n        import subprocess\n\n        subprocess.run(\n            [\"bash\", \"-c\", \"curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh\"],\n            check=True,\n        )\n        subprocess.run(\n            [\"ollama\", \"pull\", \"qwen2.5:7b\"],\n            check=True,\n            env={\"OLLAMA_MODELS\": \"/root/.ollama\"},\n        )\n\n    @modal.enter()\n    def start_server(self):\n        \"\"\"Start ollama serve as background process, wait for ready.\"\"\"\n        import subprocess, time, os, signal, requests\n\n        self._process = subprocess.Popen(\n            [\"ollama\", \"serve\"],\n            stdout=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            stderr=subprocess.DEVNULL,\n            preexec_fn=os.setsid,\n        )\n\n        # Poll until Ollama is ready (max 90s)\n        for i in range(45):\n            try:\n                r = requests.get(\"http://localhost:11434\", timeout=2)\n                if r.status_code == 200:\n                    print(f\"[spark-ollama] Ready after ~{i*2}s\")\n                    break\n            except Exception:\n                pass\n            time.sleep(2)\n        else:\n            raise RuntimeError(\"Ollama failed to start within 90s\")\n\n    @modal.exit()\n    def stop_server(self):\n        import os, signal\n\n        try:\n            os.killpg(os.getpgid(self._process.pid), signal.SIGTERM)\n        except Exception:\n            pass\n\n    @modal.web_endpoint(label=\"spark-ollama-qwen\", method=\"POST\")\n    def generate(self, body: dict):\n        \"\"\"\n        Proxy generate request to local Ollama.\n        body: { prompt: str, model?: str, options?: { temperature?, num_predict? } }\n        \"\"\"\n        import requests\n\n        payload = {\n            \"model\": body.get(\"model\", \"qwen2.5:7b\"),\n            \"prompt\": body.get(\"prompt\", \"\"),\n            \"stream\": False,\n            \"options\": body.get(\"options\", {}),\n        }\n        resp = requests.post(\n            \"http://localhost:11434/api/generate\",\n            json=payload,\n            timeout=90,\n        )\n        resp.raise_for_status()\n        return {\"response\": resp.json().get(\"response\", \"\"), \"model\": payload[\"model\"]}\n\n    @modal.web_endpoint(label=\"spark-ollama-qwen\", method=\"GET\")\n    def health(self):\n        return {\n            \"status\": \"ok\",\n            \"service\": \"spark-ollama\",\n            \"model\": \"qwen2.5:7b\",\n        }\n\n\n@app.local_entrypoint()\ndef test():\n    print(\"spark-ollama module loaded OK\")\n"}}],"api":"anthropic-messages","provider":"minimax-portal","model":"MiniMax-M2.7","usage":{"input":74682,"output":1422,"cacheRead":13593,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":89697,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774274618965}}
