{"type":"message","id":"3f6c1540","parentId":"b0027145","timestamp":"2026-03-23T14:07:13.627Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Wait, there's another issue. When `curl -fsSL https://ollama.com/install.sh | sh` runs, it installs Ollama into `/usr/local/bin`. But the next build layer won't have Ollama unless it's also in that layer. Let me check how Modal's `run_commands` works. Each `run_commands` is a separate RUN command in the Dockerfile. The files installed in one RUN persist in subsequent RUNs, so Ollama should be available after the install script runs.\n\nBut there's another consideration: the Ollama installer might download a binary and install it. It should persist in /usr/local/bin. And subsequent layers should have access to it.\n \nI'm realizing the shell pipeline won't work reliably in a RUN command due to piping behavior, so I should break this into separate RUN statements instead—one to install zstd and another to fetch and execute the Ollama installer script.\n\nActually, combining them with `&&` ensures the install script only runs if zstd installs successfully, which is cleaner. But I'm noticing that the Modal runner might have issues with character encoding in ANSI codes, so I should try redirecting stderr or using a simpler installation approach to avoid those encoding failures. zstd is installed before the Ollama script runs. I'm also realizing that `apt-get install` outputs non-ASCII characters like checkmarks and bullet points, which could cause encoding issues when Modal tries to print the build output. Let me set `LANG=C.UTF-8` during the build to handle this, and consider combining the installation commands into fewer steps to reduce output volume.\n\nActually, the real issue might be that the `•` character in Modal's internal code is being printed to the Windows console, which uses a different encoding. If I just rerun the command, the image should be cached and skip most of the build steps anyway.\n\n